Johannesburg Metrobus has been struggling since Tuesday to transport thousands of commuters in the city due to a strike by the Democratic Municipal & Allied Workers Union of South Africa (Demawusa). Four buses were stoned and two drivers were injured in the Johannesburg CBD when the strike started on Tuesday. On Wednesday morning five windows of a bus were broken after it was stoned en route to Gandhi Square after departing from the Roodepoort depot. No-one was injured. Negotiations deadlocked on Wednesdayâ€š but will resume on Thursday at 8am. Demawusa spokesperson Dion Makhura said their demands to the bus company included: Metrobus said in a statement that the South African Municipal Workers' Union (Samwu) and Independent Municipal and Allied Trade Union (Imatu) have meanwhile continued to provide transport services on a small scale despite members being intimidated. Metrobus advised commuters to make alternative travel arrangements while negotiations continue.